      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics label substantive due process \"judicial activism\" because they argue that unelected judges are effectively making new laws rather than interpreting existing ones. They contend that the Constitution does not explicitly list these rights, meaning judges are inventing them from judicial philosophy. This criticism stems from the belief that fundamental policy decisions should belong to democratically elected representatives, not the courts. Therefore, the debate centers on whether the judiciary is correctly interpreting the text or improperly legislating from the bench.",
      "source": "target",
